TalkingData AdTracking Fraud Detection Challenge¶

This is a exploratory data analysis for Kaggle's TalkingData AdTracking Fraud Detection Challenge. We are challenged to build an algorithm that predicts whether a user will download an app after clicking a mobile app ad.

The dataset¶

We are provided aproximately 200 million click data with the following features:

  • ip: ip address of click.
  • app: app id for marketing.
  • device: device type id of user mobile phone (e.g., iphone 6 plus, iphone 7, huawei mate 7, etc.)
  • os: os version id of user mobile phone
  • channel: channel id of mobile ad publisher
  • click_time: timestamp of click (UTC)
  • attributed_time: if user download the app for after clicking an ad, this is the time of the app download
  • is_attributed: the target that is to be predicted, indicating the app was downloaded

Exploring the train sample dataset¶

Let's load train.csv and explore it.

col_types = {
        'ip'            : 'uint32',

        'channel'       : 'uint16',

                 low_memory=True,
                 dtype=col_types, 
                 parse_dates=['click_time'], 
                 infer_datetime_format=True,
                 usecols = lambda x: x not in "attributed_time")
elapsed = time.time() - t
print("Time reading data: %s seconds.\n" %round(elapsed))

cols = ['ip', 'app', 'device', 'os', 'channel']

print("Fig. 1 - Cumulative number of clicks and downloads in unique features:")
plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
for idx, col in enumerate(cols):
    plt.subplot(2,3,idx+1)
    plt.title(col)
    df[col].value_counts().cumsum().sort_values().reset_index(drop=True).plot(legend=True, label = 'n_clicks')
    df.groupby(col)['is_attributed'].agg('sum').sort_values(ascending=False).cumsum().reset_index(drop=True).plot(secondary_y=True, legend=True, label = 'n_dl')
    plt.tight_layout()
    
gc.collect();

Fig. 1 - Cumulative number of clicks and downloads in unique features:

Notice from the graph that there are few apps, devices and os concentrating most clicks and downloads, while there is more variability in ip and channel. There is also some divergence in concentration of clicks and downloads in ip, app, device and channel, as follows:

IP:

  • Clicks are more concentrated than downloads
  • There are some IPs with many downloads (initial concavity)
  • There are a lot of IPs with a single download (45 degree line segment)
  • There are some IPs with no download (flat segment at the top/end)

App and Device:

  • Clicks are more concentrated than downloads, so there a few are apps and devices with many clicks and low download rates.

Channel:

  • Downloads are more concentrated than clicks; there are particular channels less prone to fraudulent clicks.

Exploring clicks and downloads¶

Let's check how clicks and downloads vary within apps, devices, os and channels. Relevant questions:

  • Which IP's concentrate most clicks? Do they have reasonable download rates?
  • Which apps and devices have many clicks and low download rates?
  • Which channels are less prone to fraudulent clicks?

Exploring IPs¶

Which IP's concentrate most clicks? Do they have reasonable download rates?

tbl = df.groupby('ip')['is_attributed'].agg(['count', 'sum']).rename(columns={"count": "n_clicks", "sum": "n_dl"})
tbl['click_pct'] = tbl['n_clicks'] / tbl['n_clicks'].sum() * 100
tbl['dl_pct'] = tbl['n_dl'] / df['is_attributed'].sum() * 100

print("Fig. 2 - Clicks and downloads by IP (%)")

plt.xlabel("% clicks")
plt.ylabel("% downloads")

Fig. 2 - Clicks and downloads by IP (%)

No particular IP holds more than 1% of clicks nor downloads. There are two IPs with more than 0.20% of clicks and less 0.03% of downloads (on yellow). Number of clicks by IP might be a relevant feature.

print("Fig. 3 - Clicks and downloads by feature (%)")

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 9))

cols = ['app', 'device', 'os', 'channel']

for idx, col in enumerate(cols):
    tbl = df.groupby(col)['is_attributed'].agg(['count', 'sum']).rename(columns={"count": "n_clicks", "sum": "n_dl"}).reset_index()
    tbl['click_pct'] = tbl['n_clicks'] / tbl['n_clicks'].sum() * 100
    tbl['dl_pct'] = tbl['n_dl'] / df['is_attributed'].sum() * 100
    tbl.sort_values(by=['n_clicks'], ascending=False).head(10)

    plt.subplot(2,2,idx+1)
    plt.scatter(tbl['click_pct'], tbl['dl_pct'], c = tbl['dl_pct'] > tbl['click_pct'])
    plt.plot( [0, tbl[['click_pct', 'dl_pct']].max().max()],[0,tbl[['click_pct', 'dl_pct']].max().max()] )

    for i in tbl.index[(tbl['click_pct']>4) | (tbl['dl_pct'] > 2)].tolist():
        plt.annotate(str(tbl.loc[i, col]), (tbl['click_pct'][i]+0.2, tbl['dl_pct'][i]+0.2))

    plt.title("Clicks and downloads within " + col)
    plt.xlabel("% clicks")
    plt.ylabel("% downloads")
    plt.tight_layout()

Fig. 3 - Clicks and downloads by feature (%)

If clicks and downloads were proportional, all points should lay over the 45 degrees line. The far down they are from the identity line, the more prone they are to fraudulent clicks. Conversely, far up from that line means more prone to downloading.

As an example, app 3 is likely to gather fraudulent clicks, while clicks on app 19 are more likely to result in a download.
Only device 0 seems to be relevant for our purposes. There are some informative os.

Apps and channels are most informative. Let's combine their information in a new plot.

New features¶

Let's create some features based on what we've seen, and then create a simple model to test their importance.

In [5]:
t = time.time()
print('Creating features by counting clicks...')

df = df.sample(frac = 0.1) # fit in memory

# Create feature identifying device 0 and drop 'device' column
df['device_0'] = (df['device'] == 0).astype('uint8')
df = df.drop(columns = 'device')

# Counting clicks
df['n_ip'] = df.groupby('ip')['ip'].transform('count')

df['n_ip_app'] = df.groupby(['ip', 'app'])['ip'].transform('count')
df['n_ip_ch'] = df.groupby(['ip', 'channel'])['ip'].transform('count')
df['n_ip_os'] = df.groupby(['ip', 'os'])['ip'].transform('count')

df['n_ip_app_ch'] = df.groupby(['ip', 'app', 'channel'])['ip'].transform('count')
df['n_ip_os_app_ch'] = df.groupby(['ip', 'os', 'app', 'channel'])['ip'].transform('count')

df['n_ip_day_hour'] = df.groupby(['ip', 'day_hour'])['ip'].transform('count')

# Interactions
df['app_channel'] = df['app'] * 1000 + df['channel']

elapsed = time.time() - t
print("Time creating features: %s seconds.\n" %round(elapsed))

Creating features by counting clicks...

In [6]:
# Time features
t = time.time()
print('Creating features based on click_time...')

df = df.sort_values(by=['ip', 'click_time'])

df['ct_lag'] = df.groupby(['ip'])['click_time'].shift(1)
df['ct_lead'] = df.groupby(['ip'])['click_time'].shift(-1)

df['td_lag'] = df['click_time'] - df['ct_lag']
df = df.drop(columns = 'ct_lag')

df['td_lead'] = df['ct_lead'] - df['click_time']
df = df.drop(columns = 'ct_lead')

df['min_td'] = df[['td_lag', 'td_lead']].min(axis=1) / pd.Timedelta(hours=1)
df = df.drop(columns = ['td_lag', 'td_lead'])

df['min_td'].fillna(max(df.min_td), inplace = True)

df = df.drop(columns = ['ip', 'click_time'])
gc.collect();

elapsed = time.time() - t
print("Time creating features: %s seconds.\n" %round(elapsed))

# Preparing data to build a LightGBM model
t = time.time()
print('Preparing data to build a LightGBM model...')

from sklearn.cross_validation import train_test_split
import lightgbm as lgb

df_train = df.sample(frac = 0.8)
df_valid = df.sample(frac = 0.2)
del df
gc.collect();

y_train = df_train.is_attributed.values
y_valid = df_valid.is_attributed.values

df_train = df_train.drop('is_attributed', axis=1)
df_valid = df_valid.drop('is_attributed', axis=1)

categorical = ['app', 'os', 'channel', 'day_hour', 'device_0']
features = [col for col in df_train.columns]

lgb_train = lgb.Dataset(df_train, y_train, feature_name = features, categorical_feature=categorical, free_raw_data=False)
#del df_train
#del y_train
#gc.collect();

lgb_valid = lgb.Dataset(df_valid, y_valid, feature_name = features, categorical_feature=categorical, free_raw_data=False)
#del df_valid
#del y_valid
#gc.collect();

# specify your configurations as a dict
params = {
    'task': 'train',
    'boosting_type': 'gbdt',
    'objective': 'binary',
    'metric': 'auc',
    'num_leaves': 7,
    'max_depth': 3,
    'min_child_samples': 100,  # Minimum number of data need in a child(min_data_in_leaf)
    'max_bin': 100,  # Number of bucketed bin for feature values
    'learning_rate': 0.1,
    'feature_fraction': 0.9,
    'bagging_fraction': 0.8,
    'bagging_freq': 5,
    'verbose': 0,
    'scale_pos_weight': 99.74 # because training data is extremely unbalanced 
}

elapsed = time.time() - t
print("Time elapsed: %s seconds.\n" %round(elapsed))

In [17]:
import shap
shap.initjs()
preds = gbm.predict(df_train.iloc[:1000,:])
shap_values = gbm.predict(df_train.iloc[:1000,:], pred_contrib=True)
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, df_train.iloc[:1000,:])

This graph shows the impact of each feature in the model output. channel, app, os, and day_hour have the most impact on output, consistent with our variable importance table shown above.

Notice, for example, that while low number of clicks by a IP (n_ip) increases predicted download probability, high number of clicks by an IP in that particular App (n_ip_app) increases predicted download probability.

Also, if a click by an ip is distant in time from any other click of that same ip (as measured by min_td), then the model tends to predict higher download probability for that click.

Let's check how those features apply to a single example.
